01:06:42.289 --> 01:06:43.289
you got to age it.
That takes years; that's a lot of capital

01:06:43.289 --> 01:06:44.289
and places to store it and so on.
Yeah, liquor has been kind of the latecomer

01:06:44.289 --> 01:06:45.289
here to the craft movement, but yeah here
it is.

01:06:45.289 --> 01:06:46.289
It's kind of just popping up.
So kind of wrapping up my talk here today.

01:06:46.289 --> 01:06:47.289
We've looked at a lot of different things
here.

01:06:47.289 --> 01:06:48.289
A lot of the key issues that have gone on
here in American society, kind of tracing

01:06:48.289 --> 01:06:49.289
how Americans have shifted over these last
76 years from a country where alcohol was

01:06:49.289 --> 01:06:50.289
once heavily stigmatized to one where we are
today where yeah, most of us drink and a lot

01:06:50.289 --> 01:06:51.289
of people are kind of fanatics about what
they drink.

01:06:51.289 --> 01:06:52.289
And so, especially people who pair food together
with whatever they like to drink.

01:06:52.289 --> 01:06:53.289
So it's a pretty significant social shift
in American society.

01:06:53.289 --> 01:06:54.289
And I think in a lot of ways, alcohol is in
fact fundamental to American society.

01:06:54.289 --> 01:06:55.289
It was really naive of the temperance movement,
especially in hindsight, to think that, "Wow,

01:06:55.289 --> 01:06:56.289
they actually wanted to ban alcohol?" And
would Americans actually not drink?

01:06:56.289 --> 01:06:57.289
I mean, alcohol's been there from the beginning.
I mean, literally, from Jamestown -- the first

01:06:57.289 --> 01:06:58.289
settlers that came to Jamestown, they didn't
want to grow tobacco.

01:06:58.289 --> 01:06:59.289
They ended up with tobacco.
They went there to grow grapes so they could

01:06:59.289 --> 01:07:00.289
challenge the French in Bordeaux.
So they were trying to basically break the

01:07:00.289 --> 01:07:01.289
French monopoly on red wine.
And it didn't work out that way and Williamsburg

01:07:01.289 --> 01:07:02.289
and that area is a terrible climate to grow
grapes; it's very humid.

01:07:02.289 --> 01:07:03.289
So they ended up with tobacco instead.
Or in 1620, when the pilgrims came here, they

01:07:03.289 --> 01:07:04.289
ended up in Plymouth.
But the first place they actually landed was

01:07:04.289 --> 01:07:05.289
what's now Provincetown, up at the very tip
of Cape Cod.

01:07:05.289 --> 01:07:06.289
And when they came ashore, the very first
thing that they did?

01:07:06.289 --> 01:07:07.289
They dug a well so they could get water so
they could brew beer.

01:07:07.289 --> 01:07:08.289
That's how you preserved your water back then.
I mean, it was low alcohol beer, three to

01:07:08.289 --> 01:07:09.289
four percent alcohol.
But you know, these people by the way, were

01:07:09.289 --> 01:07:10.289
Puritans.
People blame Prohibition on the Puritans.

01:07:10.289 --> 01:07:11.289
In fact, the Puritans drink.
It wasn't their fault that Prohibition came

01:07:11.289 --> 01:07:12.289
about, but rather from a movement that came
out centuries later. So yeah.

01:07:12.289 --> 01:07:13.289
I mean, alcohol in fact really is a fundamental
part of American society, and I think the

01:07:13.289 --> 01:07:14.289
sooner we can recognize that and the fact
that we can sooner recognize that there are

01:07:14.289 --> 01:07:15.289
in fact benefits from moderate drinking and
from socialization that ultimately leads to

01:07:15.289 --> 01:07:16.289
a better outcome for Americans overall.
I always like to end here with my favorite

01:07:16.289 --> 01:07:17.289
quote here from Homer Simpson, which is, "To
alcohol, the cause of and solution to all

01:07:17.289 --> 01:07:18.289
of life's problems."
All righty. I'll be glad to hear -- to take

01:07:18.289 --> 01:07:19.289
any questions and to answer any questions
you guys have.

