01:08:23.289 --> 01:08:24.289
And during Prohibition itself, the distillers
really got in trouble because they were the

01:08:24.289 --> 01:08:25.289
ones -- that's when the bootleggers were breaking
in, right?

01:08:25.289 --> 01:08:26.289
You got so much more profit margin by bringing
in a barrel of distilled spirits vs. wine

01:08:26.289 --> 01:08:27.289
or beer.
You make a lot more cocktails with it, right?

01:08:27.289 --> 01:08:28.289
So the biggest stigma against alcohol was
largely against spirits.

01:08:28.289 --> 01:08:29.289
And hence, the distillers -- once it became
legal again to distill -- they had kind of

01:08:29.289 --> 01:08:30.289
the toughest row to hoe.
So they agreed in the 1930's that they wouldn't

01:08:30.289 --> 01:08:31.289
advertise on television or radio.
And that held all the way until 1996, and

01:08:31.289 --> 01:08:32.289
that's when the spirits really hit a low point.
And at that point, the first company that

01:08:32.289 --> 01:08:33.289
was Seagrams said, "Okay, we have to advertise.
