Sometimes you get four people show up.
And a lot of events are kind of in between.

01:09:35.289 --> 01:09:36.289
So I think every event has a little bit of
a sacrifice or RBI element to it.

01:09:36.289 --> 01:09:37.289
As long as you're selling books, it's okay,
you know?

01:09:37.289 --> 01:09:38.289
It's okay to not have a huge audience or anything.
You had a question.

01:09:38.289 --> 01:09:39.289
Q Yeah, I was going to ask what your thoughts
are on the parallel between alcohol prohibition

01:09:39.289 --> 01:09:40.289
and marijuana prohibition currently?

01:09:40.289 --> 01:09:41.289
Garrett Peck: Good question. Everyone asks
this question here.

01:09:41.289 --> 01:09:42.289
He had asked here about the prohibition against
alcohol vs. the drug wars.

01:09:42.289 --> 01:09:43.289
And I do actually cut that at all in the book
itself, but it's a very timely question.

01:09:43.289 --> 01:09:44.289
I think it's fascinating to point out the
parallel or nonparallel between Prohibition

01:09:44.289 --> 01:09:45.289
and the drug wars of today.
Even during Prohibition, and by the way I

01:09:45.289 --> 01:09:46.289
think largely Prohibition and the drug wars
are largely about enforcement, right?

01:09:46.289 --> 01:09:47.289
It's about trying to keep people from getting
a hold of products.

01:09:47.289 --> 01:09:48.289
But never deals with the ultimate question
of market size -- the demand side of the equation,

01:09:48.289 --> 01:09:49.289
"Why do people want to drink? Why do people
want to get high?"

01:09:49.289 --> 01:09:50.289
And ultimately I think, if people want to
do it, they're going to do it.

01:09:50.289 --> 01:09:51.289
That's my fundamental conclusion.
Even during Prohibition itself -- this is

01:09:51.289 --> 01:09:52.289
really kind of shocking -- personal possession
of alcohol was never illegal.

01:09:52.289 --> 01:09:53.289
You could always have it in your home.
You can make your own wine back during Prohibition,

01:09:53.289 --> 01:09:54.289
and many people did.
All the 18th Amendment did was outlaw the

01:09:54.289 --> 01:09:55.289
manufacture, sale, and transportation of alcohol,
but the temperance movement -- at least give

01:09:55.289 --> 01:09:56.289
them some credit -- they realized, "Okay,
people still want a certain amount of freedom

01:09:56.289 --> 01:09:57.289
still to drink in their own homes.
Therefore it's not illegal to actually possess

01:09:57.289 --> 01:09:58.289
this stuff."
You look at kind of the non-parallels to the

01:09:58.289 --> 01:09:59.289
drug wars today where we've criminalized even
the possession.

01:09:59.289 --> 01:10:00.289
So hence, we've filled our prisons full of
people who are largely low-level drug offenders.

01:10:00.289 --> 01:10:01.289
You know?
Most of these people are not druglords and

01:10:01.289 --> 01:10:02.289
stuff.
They're simply people who got caught a couple

01:10:02.289 --> 01:10:03.289
of times smoking marijuana or whatever.
And is that the best policy, because incarcerating

01:10:03.289 --> 01:10:04.289
people is horribly expensive?
And does it ever actually deal with the demand

01:10:04.289 --> 01:10:05.289
side of the equation?
When you can deal with it through education,

01:10:05.289 --> 01:10:06.289
with treatment, or ultimately with licensing
it, you know?

01:10:06.289 --> 01:10:07.289
A lot of people I know are getting more and
more towards that point, especially, I think

01:10:07.289 --> 01:10:08.289
my generation.
Generation X -- we're kind of libertarians.

01:10:08.289 --> 01:10:09.289
And people are sort of like, "Hmm. Shouldn't
gay marriage be legal?

01:10:09.289 --> 01:10:10.289
Shouldn't alcohol be legal? Shouldn't marijuana
be legal?"

01:10:10.289 --> 01:10:11.289
People have really changed their mindsets
significantly.

01:10:11.289 --> 01:10:12.289
A lot of these social questions now in American
society.

01:10:12.289 --> 01:10:13.289
So. Yeah, it's definitely a relevant question
here.

01:10:13.289 --> 01:10:14.289
And I think we'll see where that goes over
the next few years.

01:10:14.289 --> 01:10:15.289
Especially as more and more states adopt medical
marijuana for use and more and more people

01:10:15.289 --> 01:10:16.289
are finding -- kind of coming out as occasional
tokers, you know?

01:10:16.289 --> 01:10:17.289
Q Just one more quick question.
Have you ever -- going off that -- maybe drawn

01:10:17.289 --> 01:10:18.289
the parallel to the movement of staying a
little more strong to restrict soda and other

01:10:18.289 --> 01:10:19.289
sugary beverages?
If you think about that new advertising campaign

01:10:19.289 --> 01:10:20.289
in university where it shows them pouring
soda and just how much fat and to not drink

01:10:20.289 --> 01:10:21.289
soda?
Do you kind of have the same opinion about

01:10:21.289 --> 01:10:22.289
the demand side of something like that?

01:10:22.289 --> 01:10:23.289
Garrett Peck: I don't really examine that
question myself.

01:10:23.289 --> 01:10:24.289
I think certainly soda is probably one of
the reasons -- among other reasons -- why

01:10:24.289 --> 01:10:25.289
Americans are facing the obesity epidemic
in the country.

01:10:25.289 --> 01:10:26.289
And I think obesity is in fact our biggest
by far -- no pun intended -- public health

01:10:26.289 --> 01:10:27.289
issue now.
You know Americans -- our portion sizes are

01:10:27.289 --> 01:10:28.289
out of control.
Americans drive everywhere now.

01:10:28.289 --> 01:10:29.289
We don't exercise when we go to and from work.
And we also have desks now.

01:10:29.289 --> 01:10:30.289
So just it's a huge lifestyle question I think
ultimately, but soda is certainly a part of

01:10:30.289 --> 01:10:31.289
it.
I haven't really myself examined the question

01:10:31.289 --> 01:10:32.289
of whether or not we should ban sodas in school
or not.

01:10:32.289 --> 01:10:33.289
Actually, I personally stopped drinking sodas
over a decade ago.

01:10:33.289 --> 01:10:34.289
But just more because I would get a big sugar
rush and then I would just collapse.

01:10:34.289 --> 01:10:35.289
So I decided, "Okay, I'm not going to drink
that anymore. I'll just drink good whiskey."

