01:10:36.289 --> 01:10:37.289
Q I have one more question.
You mentioned that women didn't really start

01:10:37.289 --> 01:10:38.289
drinking until the 20's.
I guess if you look back at the century preceeding

01:10:38.289 --> 01:10:39.289
that -- the 1800s -- was it still predominantly
men that drank?

01:10:39.289 --> 01:10:40.289
I mean the rank and file -- did women really
not drink first couple hundred years of this

01:10:40.289 --> 01:10:41.289
country, or?

01:10:41.289 --> 01:10:42.289
Garrett Peck: Yeah, the question was about
women and drinking and women didn't really

01:10:42.289 --> 01:10:43.289
start drinking until the 1920's in American
society.

01:10:43.289 --> 01:10:44.289
But what was the role of women before then.
Did women in fact drink?

01:10:44.289 --> 01:10:45.289
I think some women certainly did drink.
But largely, drinking was the purview of men,

01:10:45.289 --> 01:10:46.289
because men, at that point, went to the saloon
or the tavern.

01:10:46.289 --> 01:10:47.289
So they'd go outside of the house.
And you know, where the temperance movement

01:10:47.289 --> 01:10:48.289
came from was this church-based response to
the binge drinking that was going on.

01:10:48.289 --> 01:10:49.289
And if you look at it per capita, at the peak
of the binge -- which was about 1820, 1830

01:10:49.289 --> 01:10:50.289
 -- when there was no tax on whiskey at all
and it was everywhere, the actual per capita

01:10:50.289 --> 01:10:51.289
amount of alcohol -- if you looked at just
the men who were drinking at the time -- it

01:10:51.289 --> 01:10:52.289
was about eight times what we are drinking
per capita today.

01:10:52.289 --> 01:10:53.289
I mean, a huge social issue; men were drinking
themselves to death.

01:10:53.289 --> 01:10:54.289
And yes, it was largely men, because they
were the ones who would go out to the saloons

01:10:54.289 --> 01:10:55.289
and taverns and women weren't welcome in taverns.
You might have even seen at some places like,

01:10:55.289 --> 01:10:56.289
if you ever go to San Francisco, go to Elixir;
it's in the Mission District.

01:10:56.289 --> 01:10:57.289
I gave a talk there last week.
And they had a separate entrance for women

01:10:57.289 --> 01:10:58.289
only.
I think it's the second oldest saloon in the

01:10:58.289 --> 01:10:59.289
city, 1850's sometime.
Because wives were allowed to go in there

01:10:59.289 --> 01:11:00.289
with a growler.
Today there's a bottle called the growler.

01:11:00.289 --> 01:11:01.289
It's a big four pints.
But back then a growler was a bucket.

01:11:01.289 --> 01:11:02.289
And the wives or kids would be sent to basically
the service entrance of the bar and if you

01:11:02.289 --> 01:11:03.289
go use this one entrance -- because women
weren't allowed inside the bar -- they would

01:11:03.289 --> 01:11:04.289
fill up the growler and that was for home
consumption.

01:11:04.289 --> 01:11:05.289
They would take it home for their husbands.
So that was the only way women could in fact

01:11:05.289 --> 01:11:06.289
go inside of a bar, you know?
Including at that bar Elixir.

01:11:06.289 --> 01:11:07.289
New York City there was a very famous bar
out there called McSorley's, in the 1850's

01:11:07.289 --> 01:11:08.289
Irish bar.
And women weren't allowed in there until around

01:11:08.289 --> 01:11:09.289
1970 or so.
So yeah. Need to cut off?

